     1	# How To Build An Assistant
     2	
     3	Date: 2026-04-11
     4	Revised: 2026-04-11 (spec-reconciliation pass ŌĆö all examples updated to match canonical specs)
     5	
     6	> **Canonical source of truth:** Package specs in `docs/specs/` override any example or description in this document. If an API name, import path, or assembly pattern in this document conflicts with a spec, trust the spec. See `docs/architecture/spec-reconciliation-rules.md` for the full replacement table.
     7	
     8	## Purpose
     9	
    10	This document explains how a consumer should think about building an assistant on top of this SDK once implementation begins.
    11	
    12	It is intentionally architectural. It does not assume package code exists yet.
    13	
    14	## Start With One Assistant Definition
    15	
    16	A product should model one user-facing assistant as:
    17	
    18	- one assistant identity
    19	- one assistant session model
    20	- zero or more internal specialists
    21	- optional memory and proactive capabilities
    22	
    23	The external user experience should remain one coherent assistant even if multiple internal runtimes contribute.
    24	
    25	## Expected Package Imports
    26	
    27	Consumers should expect to import only the packages they need.
    28	
    29	Canonical import shape for v1 packages (core, sessions, surfaces):
    30	
    31	```ts
    32	// Core
    33	import { createAssistant } from "@relay-assistant/core";
    34	import type {
    35	  AssistantDefinition,
    36	  AssistantRuntime,
    37	  InboundMessage,
    38	  OutboundEvent,
    39	  CapabilityHandler,
    40	  CapabilityContext,
    41	} from "@relay-assistant/core";
    42	
    43	// Sessions
    44	import {
    45	  createSessionStore,
    46	  InMemorySessionStoreAdapter,
    47	  resolveSession,
    48	  createDefaultAffinityResolver,
    49	} from "@relay-assistant/sessions";
    50	import type { Session, SessionStore } from "@relay-assistant/sessions";
    51	
    52	// Surfaces
    53	import { createSurfaceRegistry } from "@relay-assistant/surfaces";
    54	import type {
    55	  SurfaceConnection,
    56	  SurfaceRegistry,
    57	  SurfaceAdapter,
    58	  SurfaceCapabilities,
    59	  SurfaceFormatHook,
    60	} from "@relay-assistant/surfaces";
    61	```
    62	
    63	Later packages (v1.1+) follow the same pattern:
    64	
    65	```ts
    66	import { createMemoryStore } from "@relay-assistant/memory";
    67	import { createProactiveEngine } from "@relay-assistant/proactive";
    68	import { createCoordinator } from "@relay-assistant/coordination";
    69	import { createConnectivityLayer } from "@relay-assistant/connectivity";
    70	import { createActionPolicy } from "@relay-assistant/policy";
    71	```
    72	
    73	The names above for future packages are illustrative. v1 names (`createAssistant`, `createSessionStore`, `createSurfaceRegistry`) are spec-confirmed.
    74	
    75	## Minimum Build Order
    76	
    77	Build an assistant in this order:
    78	
    79	1. define the assistant identity and runtime boundary in `@relay-assistant/core`
    80	2. define how inbound activity maps into an assistant session via `@relay-assistant/sessions`
    81	3. attach surfaces through `@relay-assistant/surfaces`
    82	4. add memory via `@relay-assistant/memory` if continuity is needed
    83	5. add proactive behavior via `@relay-assistant/proactive` if the assistant should act when the user is not actively messaging
    84	6. add specialist orchestration via `@relay-assistant/coordination` if one assistant needs multiple internal agents
    85	7. add focused internal signaling via `@relay-assistant/connectivity` when multiple subsystems or specialists must coordinate efficiently
    86	8. govern external actions with `@relay-assistant/policy`
    87	
    88	## What The Product Must Supply
    89	
    90	The SDK should not replace product logic.
    91	
    92	Each product still supplies:
    93	
    94	- domain prompts and instruction sets
    95	- product-specific tools and workflows
    96	- domain-specific watcher definitions
    97	- UI or surface presentation choices
    98	- business policy and escalation rules
    99	
   100	## Recommended Mental Model
   101	
   102	Think in three layers:
   103	
   104	### Layer 1: Relay foundation
   105	
   106	Use Relay family repos for transport, webhook verification, delivery, auth, scheduler substrate, and low-level action dispatch.
   107	
   108	### Layer 2: Assistant SDK
   109	
   110	Use this repo for assistant runtime contracts and reusable assistant behavior.
   111	
   112	### Layer 3: Product assistant
   113	
   114	Use the product repo for the actual product experience.
   115	
   116	## Basic Assembly Pattern
   117	
   118	A typical product assembles an assistant in five steps:
   119	
   120	1. declare an `AssistantDefinition` with `id`, `name`, and `capabilities` (`Record<string, CapabilityHandler>`)
   121	2. create a `SessionStore` via `createSessionStore({ adapter })`
   122	3. create a `SurfaceRegistry` via `createSurfaceRegistry()` and register one or more `SurfaceConnection` objects
   123	4. create the runtime via `createAssistant(definition, { inbound: surfaceRegistry, outbound: surfaceRegistry })` ŌĆö the surface registry implements both relay adapter interfaces
   124	5. call `runtime.register("sessions", sessionStore)` then `runtime.start()`
   125	
   126	Future subsystems (memory, proactive, coordination, policy) are also registered on the runtime via `runtime.register(name, subsystem)`.
   127	
   128	## Skeletal Assembly Example
   129	
   130	```ts
   131	import { createAssistant } from "@relay-assistant/core";
   132	import type {
   133	  AssistantDefinition,
   134	  InboundMessage,
   135	  CapabilityContext,
   136	} from "@relay-assistant/core";
   137	import {
   138	  createSessionStore,
   139	  InMemorySessionStoreAdapter,
   140	  resolveSession,
   141	  createDefaultAffinityResolver,
   142	} from "@relay-assistant/sessions";
   143	import type { SessionStore } from "@relay-assistant/sessions";
   144	import { createSurfaceRegistry } from "@relay-assistant/surfaces";
   145	import type { SurfaceConnection, SurfaceCapabilities } from "@relay-assistant/surfaces";
   146	
   147	// Step 1: Define assistant identity and capabilities
   148	const definition: AssistantDefinition = {
   149	  id: "my-assistant",
   150	  name: "My Assistant",
   151	  capabilities: {
   152	    chat: async (message: InboundMessage, context: CapabilityContext) => {
   153	      const store = context.runtime.get<SessionStore>("sessions");
   154	      const session = await resolveSession(
   155	        message,
   156	        store,
   157	        createDefaultAffinityResolver(store),
   158	      );
   159	      await store.touch(session.id);
   160	
   161	      // Targeted send: reply to the originating surface
   162	      await context.runtime.emit({
   163	        surfaceId: message.surfaceId,
   164	        sessionId: session.id,
   165	        text: "response text", // product logic here
   166	      });
   167	    },
   168	  },
   169	};
   170	
   171	// Step 2: Create session store
   172	const sessionStore = createSessionStore({
   173	  adapter: new InMemorySessionStoreAdapter(),
   174	});
   175	
   176	// Step 3: Define and register surface connections
   177	const slackCapabilities: SurfaceCapabilities = {
   178	  markdown: false,
   179	  richBlocks: true,
   180	  attachments: true,
   181	  streaming: false,
   182	  maxResponseLength: 3000,
   183	};
   184	
   185	const slackConnection: SurfaceConnection = {
   186	  id: "my-assistant-slack",
   187	  type: "slack",
   188	  state: "registered",
   189	  capabilities: slackCapabilities,
   190	  adapter: slackAdapter, // provided by relay foundation or product code
   191	};
   192	
   193	const surfaceRegistry = createSurfaceRegistry();
   194	surfaceRegistry.register(slackConnection);
   195	
   196	// Step 4: Create runtime ŌĆö surfaces implement both relay adapter interfaces
   197	const runtime = createAssistant(definition, {
   198	  inbound: surfaceRegistry,
   199	  outbound: surfaceRegistry,
   200	});
   201	
   202	// Step 5: Register subsystems and start
   203	runtime.register("sessions", sessionStore);
   204	await runtime.start();
   205	```
   206	
   207	The example above is spec-conformant for v1. Future packages (memory, proactive, etc.) register the same way: `runtime.register("memory", memoryStore)`.
   208	
   209	## Graceful Degradation Guidance
   210	
   211	Consumers should assume that some assistant subsystems will be temporarily unavailable.
   212	
   213	Examples:
   214	- if memory is unavailable, the assistant should continue with reduced continuity rather than fail closed for every request
   215	- if proactive scheduling is unavailable, inbound interactions should still work normally
   216	- if coordination fails mid-turn, the assistant should prefer a narrower single-agent answer over total failure when safe
   217	- if one surface is degraded, the session should remain intact for other attached surfaces
   218	
   219	## What To Avoid
   220	
   221	Do not:
   222	
   223	- couple assistant runtime contracts directly to one surface
   224	- put domain logic into shared SDK packages just because multiple products need something vaguely similar
   225	- bypass session contracts by using raw thread IDs as the only continuity key
   226	- assume any future cloud service exists
   227	- use stale API names (`AssistantConfig`, `handleMessage`, `createSurfaceConnection`, `assistant.attachSurface`, `sessions.resume`, `sessions.close`) ŌĆö see `docs/architecture/spec-reconciliation-rules.md` Rule 1 for the full replacement table
   228	
   229	## Product Examples
